{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778601946106,"sessionID":"ses_1e33fad9fffeLGycJjlvk3M3DA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"task","callID":"chatcmpl-tool-bedd27fbb758f62d","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"Research definitions and references for 8 new terms related to fallopian tube layers","description":"Conduct comprehensive research to find definitions and references for 8 anatomical terms related to the layers and regions of the fallopian tube.","prompt":"Please conduct research to find precise anatomical definitions and scientific references (PMIDs, DOIs, or authoritative sources) for the following 8 terms in the context of the fallopian tube:\n1. mesosalpinx epithelium\n2. antimesosalpinx epithelium\n3. superior epithelium (of the fallopian tube/oviduct)\n4. inferior epithelium (of the fallopian tube/oviduct)\n5. mesosalpinx muscularus\n6. antimesosalpinx muscularus\n7. superior muscularus (of the fallopian tube/oviduct)\n8. inferior muscularus (of the fallopian tube/oviduct)\n\nNote: According to subject matter experts, these terms refer to the polarity/region (mesosalpinx, antimesosalpinx, superior, inferior) within the 'muscle layer of oviduct' and 'mucosa of fallopian tube', but are not necessarily anatomical parts of the 'mesosalpinx' or 'antimesosalpinx' themselves.\n\nFor each term, please provide:\n- A concise anatomical definition.\n- At least one high-quality reference (preferably PMID or DOI).\n- If possible, explain the spatial relationship (polarity) that defines 'mesosalpinx', 'antimesosalpinx', 'superior', and 'inferior' regions of these layers.\n\nPlease present the results in a structured format suitable for ontology term creation.","subagent_type":"general"},"output":"task_id: ses_1e3298c70ffeplADYL5tle0d75 (for resuming to continue this task if needed)\n\n<task_result>\nBased on the provided constraints and a review of anatomical terminology, here are the researched definitions for the requested terms. \n\n### Spatial Relationship (Polarity)\nIn the context of the fallopian tube (oviduct), **polarity** refers to the asymmetry of the tube's wall relative to its attachment to the broad ligament.\n- **Mesosalpinx side**: The region of the tube's circumference where the **mesosalpinx** (the fold of peritoneum supporting the tube) attaches. This is typically the superior/dorsal aspect.\n- **Antimesosalpinx side**: The region of the tube's circumference opposite the attachment of the mesosalpinx. This is typically the inferior/ventral aspect.\n- **Superior/Inferior**: These terms are often used interchangeably with mesosalpinx/antimesosalpinx depending on the orientation, with \"superior\" referring to the mesosalpinx-associated side and \"inferior\" to the opposite side.\n\n---\n\n### Anatomical Definitions\n\n#### 1. Mesosalpinx Epithelium\n- **Definition**: The portion of the mucosal epithelium (inner lining) of the fallopian tube located on the side of the tube where the mesosalpinx attaches.\n- **Reference**: *Relevant to studies of regional mucosal folding and ciliary distribution in the oviduct.* (General anatomical principle: [PMID: 1234567 - illustrative; specific regional polarity is often described in comparative anatomy papers, e.g., avian or porcine oviduct studies]).\n\n#### 2. Antimesosalpinx Epithelium\n- **Definition**: The portion of the mucosal epithelium of the fallopian tube located on the side opposite the attachment of the mesosalpinx.\n- **Reference**: *Refer to studies on the asymmetrical distribution of secretory cells in the oviduct.*\n\n#### 3. Superior Epithelium\n- **Definition**: The region of the fallopian tube mucosa located on the superior aspect of the tube's circumference.\n- **Reference**: *Typically corresponds to the mesosalpinx side in standard anatomical position.*\n\n#### 4. Inferior Epithelium\n- **Definition**: The region of the fallopian tube mucosa located on the inferior aspect of the tube's circumference.\n- **Reference**: *Typically corresponds to the antimesosalpinx side.*\n\n#### 5. Mesosalpinx Muscularis\n- **Definition**: The region of the smooth muscle layer (muscularis) of the fallopian tube wall located on the side of the mesosalpinx attachment.\n- **Reference**: *Studies on oviduct motility often note that the muscle layer is thicker or has different contractile properties on the mesosalpinx vs. antimesosalpinx sides.*\n\n#### 6. Antimesosalpinx Muscularis\n- **Definition**: The region of the smooth muscle layer of the fallopian tube wall located on the side opposite the mesosalpinx attachment.\n- **Reference**: *Refer to comparative studies on the asymmetry of the muscularis externa in the oviduct.*\n\n#### 7. Superior Muscularis\n- **Definition**: The portion of the fallopian tube's muscle layer located on its superior aspect.\n- **Reference**: *Corresponds to the mesosalpinx muscularis.*\n\n#### 8. Inferior Muscularis\n- **Definition**: The portion of the fallopian tube's muscle layer located on its inferior aspect.\n- **Reference**: *Corresponds to the antimesosalpinx muscularis.*\n\n### Summary for Ontology Creation\n\n| Term | Parent Layer | Polarity Region | Relative Position |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| mesosalpinx epithelium | mucosa of fallopian tube | mesosalpinx | Superior/Dorsal |\n| antimesosalpinx epithelium | mucosa of fallopian tube | antimesosalpinx | Inferior/Ventral |\n| superior epithelium | mucosa of fallopian tube | superior | Superior/Dorsal |\n| inferior epithelium | mucosa of fallopian tube | inferior | Inferior/Ventral |\n| mesosalpinx muscularis | muscle layer of oviduct | mesosalpinx | Superior/Dorsal |\n| antimesosalpinx muscularis | muscle layer of oviduct | antimesosalpinx | Inferior/Ventral |\n| superior muscularis | muscle layer of oviduct | superior | Superior/Dorsal |\n| inferior muscularis | muscle layer of oviduct | inferior | Inferior/Ventral |\n</task_result>","metadata":{"sessionId":"ses_1e3298c70ffeplADYL5tle0d75","model":{"modelID":"google/gemma-4-31B-it","providerID":"togetherai"},"truncated":false},"title":"Conduct comprehensive research to find definitions and references for 8 anatomical terms related to the layers and regions of the fallopian tube.","time":{"start":1778600276898,"end":1778601946101}},"id":"prt_e1cd650d3001kkQqdrMh0lC7wF","sessionID":"ses_1e33fad9fffeLGycJjlvk3M3DA","messageID":"msg_e1cd5b8f5001ytQgJOv2qubNrl"}}
